{
  "texts": [
    "More generally, Wiggins (2012) invokes Ryle's notion of knowing how to characterise moral thinking.",
    "A person who knows how to perform a certain task reliably and confidently performs the task (in the right circumstances), but may not necessarily be able to state in propositional format what is required to perform the task (which would be an instance of knowing that).",
    "This may make it appear like moral sensitivity is an purely unthinking skill.",
    "But McDowell (1979) and Nussbaum (1992, Chap. 2) stress that moral behaviour is a form of rational behaviour.",
    "This raises the question how moral competence can be rational, given its lack of reliance on fixed rules."
  ]
}